WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.457 --> 00:00:02.790
(whooshing)

00:00:04.957 --> 00:00:07.540
(upbeat music)

00:00:30.380 --> 00:00:32.023
- My name is Rui de Figueiredo.

00:00:32.975 --> 00:00:34.520
I am a Emeritus faculty member

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:36.350
in both the Haas School

00:00:36.350 --> 00:00:39.570
and Department of Political
Science here at Berkeley.

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:43.041
I'm also the Chair of the
Weinstock Lecture Committee.

00:00:43.041 --> 00:00:45.370
Along with the graduate division

00:00:45.370 --> 00:00:48.060
and the graduate counsel
of the Academic Senate,

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:52.140
I am very pleased to welcome
Governor Jennifer Granholm.

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:55.400
This year's speaker in the
Barbara Weinstock lectures

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.170
on the morals of trade.

00:00:57.170 --> 00:01:01.100
Before I properly introduce
Governor Granholm.

00:01:01.100 --> 00:01:03.307
Let me first take a moment to tell you

00:01:03.307 --> 00:01:05.610
how the endowment supporting the lectures

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:08.240
came to the University
at California, Berkeley.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:12.430
In 1902, Harris Weinstock
a well known business man

00:01:12.430 --> 00:01:14.240
based in Sacramento,

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.710
provided the University
of California with a fund.

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:18.820
In honor of his wife Barbara

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:20.940
to support an annual public lecture

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:23.670
on the morals of trade.

00:01:23.670 --> 00:01:25.380
The way he explained his motivations

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:27.523
in an article that was written

00:01:27.523 --> 00:01:30.827
after the first lecture
in 1904, was as follows,

00:01:30.827 --> 00:01:33.030
"Thus hope is in the air,

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:35.320
and there is a better
and cleaner day in store

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:37.810
for all destined to spend their lives

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:39.520
in commercial pursuits.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:40.900
The thing to do at this hour

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:42.640
is to accelerate the movement

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:45.000
and to bring this hoped for day

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.023
as near to our own as possible."

00:01:48.023 --> 00:01:51.600
The California University lecture ship

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.163
on the morals of trade is a
small effort in that direction.

00:01:56.410 --> 00:01:59.360
Others who have delivered
the Weinstock lecture

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:02.312
includes consumer advocate Ralph Nader,

00:02:02.312 --> 00:02:06.020
member of the British
Parliament Neil Kinnock,

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:08.320
Nobel Laureate Amartya Sen,

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:11.980
former U.S. Secretary
of Labor Robert Reich,

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:13.930
former Secretary of the U.S. Department

00:02:14.821 --> 00:02:17.100
of Health and Human
Services Kathleen Sebelius,

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:21.490
and most recently nutritionist
and author Marion Nestle

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:25.147
and today's speaker is as accomplished

00:02:25.147 --> 00:02:28.120
as the previous lecturers.

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:31.290
A few words abut today's
distinguished speaker.

00:02:31.290 --> 00:02:33.340
A transformative politician,

00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:35.160
Governor Jennifer Granholm served

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.560
as the former 47th Governor of Michigan

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:41.210
leading the state through
a period of unprecedented

00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:42.773
economic challenge and change.

00:02:43.748 --> 00:02:45.790
Governor Granholm became the first woman

00:02:45.790 --> 00:02:49.010
to be elected as Governor
of Michigan in 2002

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:52.020
and in 2006, Governor
Granholm was reelected

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:54.260
with the largest number of votes ever cast

00:02:54.260 --> 00:02:57.150
for Governor in the state of Michigan.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:03:00.290
She served as Governor
of Michigan until 2011,

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:02.210
and prior to be elected Governor,

00:03:02.210 --> 00:03:05.150
she was the state of
Michigan Attorney General

00:03:05.150 --> 00:03:07.794
from 1998 to 2002.

00:03:07.794 --> 00:03:09.911
After leaving public office,

00:03:09.911 --> 00:03:13.000
Governor Granholm joined the faculty here

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.020
at the University of California, Berkeley

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:17.100
as a distinguished adjunct professor

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:18.357
at both the Law School

00:03:18.357 --> 00:03:20.880
and the Goldman School of Public Policy

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:22.290
and as a senior research fellow

00:03:22.290 --> 00:03:24.690
at Berkeley Energy and Climate Institute

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:26.290
also known as BECI,

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:29.250
and the center for Information
Technology Research

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.710
in the Interest of Society, or CITRIS.

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:35.000
In addition, she is a senior contributor

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.240
and many of you might
have seen her on CNN,

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:39.170
is the managing partner
of the Sustainability

00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:40.783
group of Ridgelane,

00:03:41.897 --> 00:03:44.910
is the CEO of Granholm Associates,

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:46.410
and serves on several boards

00:03:47.296 --> 00:03:49.770
of start up companies and
non profit organizations.

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:52.210
She's also the co author of
the political best seller

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:54.630
a Governor's Story: The Fight for Jobs

00:03:54.630 --> 00:03:56.410
and America's Economic Future,

00:03:56.410 --> 00:03:58.900
and was co-chair of Hillary Clinton's

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:02.420
2016 presidential transition team.

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:04.695
She's an honors graduate from

00:04:04.695 --> 00:04:06.060
the University California, Berkeley,

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:07.233
and Harvard Law School.

00:04:08.283 --> 00:04:10.560
She has honorary degrees from
the University of Michigan,

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:13.740
Wayne State University,
Mary Grove College,

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:15.600
and Michigan State University.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:17.120
She has received dozens of awards

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:19.380
for her leadership over the years

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:20.920
of public service.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.680
She's also the chair of
the American Jobs Project.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:25.423
A multi state research initiative,

00:04:26.342 --> 00:04:29.180
on creating industrial
clusters in clean energy.

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:30.720
As a member of Berkeley's Work

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.440
in the Age of Intelligent Tools work group

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:35.270
she has been researching
ways to ensure that

00:04:35.270 --> 00:04:38.110
automation and artificial intelligence

00:04:38.110 --> 00:04:42.340
are not threats to equality,
but enablers of it.

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:43.670
Her lecture today will identify

00:04:43.670 --> 00:04:45.450
some of the most interesting policy ideas

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:48.030
to address problems of displaced workers,

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:50.370
the skills gap, and resulting inequality

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:55.350
in the age of robots and AI,
or artificial intelligence.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:58.117
It is truly a pleasure and
an honor to have her here

00:04:58.117 --> 00:05:01.820
and for me to welcome Governor
Granholm to the stage.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:02.888
Thank you.

00:05:02.888 --> 00:05:06.510
(audience applause)

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:11.210
- I am really very happy to
be talking about an issue

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:14.816
that has been so important to the Midwest,

00:05:14.816 --> 00:05:19.150
and to anybody who comes
from a place or a family

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:22.471
where this issue about trade

00:05:22.471 --> 00:05:26.270
has impacted the family wellbeing,

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:28.970
and we know in Michigan a ton of those.

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:32.270
I want to start with a story.

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:35.220
I am totally obsessed about this question,

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:38.430
about jobs, and how you
create jobs in America

00:05:38.430 --> 00:05:40.230
in the global economy,

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:42.930
and because I was Michigan Governor

00:05:42.930 --> 00:05:47.440
from 2002, two terms, to end of 2010,

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:49.300
beginning of 2011,

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:53.550
I was there at a pretty amazing time.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:56.370
There was the bankruptcies
in the auto industry,

00:05:56.370 --> 00:05:58.530
which were preceded by the bankruptcies

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:00.540
in the suppliers to the auto industry,

00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:05.178
and when I came into office
at the beginning of 2003,

00:06:05.178 --> 00:06:07.802
George Bush was president,

00:06:07.802 --> 00:06:10.794
and at that time we were just coming out

00:06:10.794 --> 00:06:13.110
of a national recession,

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:15.810
and in Michigan the old adage goes

00:06:15.810 --> 00:06:17.960
that when the nation catches a cold

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:19.413
Michigan catches pneumonia,

00:06:20.706 --> 00:06:22.360
because we make large products,

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:25.980
and those large products
don't sell during a recession,

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:28.230
but of course at the end of a recession,

00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:31.420
when you come out, there's
a pent up demand for them.

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:33.050
Like vehicles.

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:35.750
So the notion is, when you
come out of a recession,

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:38.090
then you're gonna see a lot of jobs.

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:40.230
You're gonna see a lot more vehicles made,

00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:42.200
because those factories
will start humming again,

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.150
and for politicians our
advisors were saying,

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:47.900
oh what a great time to be Governor,

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:50.320
because all these jobs will be created,

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:52.070
and we'll be able to
take the credit for it.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:53.120
Fantastic!

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:57.710
In fact, at the beginning of a year,

00:06:57.710 --> 00:06:58.890
when a Governor comes in,

00:06:58.890 --> 00:07:01.390
you have to give a budget address

00:07:01.390 --> 00:07:03.290
to the state legislature,

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:05.460
and the experts were saying

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:08.030
that by the end of my
first year in office,

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:10.100
by the end of 2003,

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:13.630
that you would see a huge
amount of job creation,

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:16.660
and that it was gonna be all okay,

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:18.180
because our unemployment rate at that time

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:19.710
was pretty high.

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:22.300
The end of 2003 comes around

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:24.710
and I didn't see a whole lot.

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:27.010
We didn't see a whole lot of job creation,

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:29.220
and I thought what's going on here?

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:30.900
Then I get a call from the guy

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:33.050
who is the head of the Michigan

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:35.070
Economic Development Corporation,

00:07:35.070 --> 00:07:36.840
which is the public private entity

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:39.260
that helps businesses come to Michigan

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:43.210
and he says, Gov, we've got a big problem

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:44.796
and I said what is it?

00:07:44.796 --> 00:07:47.164
He said there is a little
community in Michigan,

00:07:47.164 --> 00:07:51.134
Greenville, and Greenville
has a population

00:07:51.134 --> 00:07:54.037
of about 8,000 people,

00:07:54.037 --> 00:07:56.950
and in that little town,

00:07:56.950 --> 00:08:00.311
there is a huge refrigerator factory.

00:08:00.311 --> 00:08:04.578
Refrigerator factory
is owned by Electrolux,

00:08:04.578 --> 00:08:09.410
and they say that they are about to move

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:11.450
to go to Mexico,

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:12.850
and I said wait, wait, wait.

00:08:14.466 --> 00:08:15.819
8,000 people.

00:08:15.819 --> 00:08:16.683
How many people work in that factory?

00:08:17.675 --> 00:08:18.508
He said almost 3,000.

00:08:19.350 --> 00:08:22.380
3,000 people in a town of 8,000.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:24.180
That's like a one company town

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:29.130
when you consider parents,
grandparents, kids, et cetera.

00:08:29.130 --> 00:08:31.418
In fact, Greenville had called itself

00:08:31.418 --> 00:08:35.050
the refrigerator capital of North America,

00:08:35.050 --> 00:08:37.530
because in fact, Electrolux was

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:40.314
the largest refrigerator
factory in North America

00:08:40.314 --> 00:08:43.533
in that little tiny town in Greenville.

00:08:43.533 --> 00:08:45.710
When he said they were gonna go to Mexico

00:08:45.710 --> 00:08:48.240
and I was the new Governor, I said no way!

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:50.660
We're not gonna allow this
to happen on my watch.

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:52.070
I'm Governor.

00:08:52.070 --> 00:08:54.730
We're gonna bring my cabinet to Greenville

00:08:54.730 --> 00:08:59.730
and we will make Electrolux
an offer they can't refuse!

00:08:59.950 --> 00:09:02.470
Well not like a Chris Christie offer.

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:04.620
I know what you're thinking.

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.640
I'm talking about incentives
and stuff like that.

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:07.743
What Governors do.

00:09:08.770 --> 00:09:10.550
We brought my whole cabinet to Greenville

00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:12.090
and we went to the City Hall

00:09:13.115 --> 00:09:15.740
which was probably a quarter
of the size of this room,

00:09:15.740 --> 00:09:19.410
and we all sat around
this big square table

00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:23.100
and everybody who was anybody
in Greenville was there.

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:27.380
Mayor, City Manager, the head of the UAW,

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:29.170
who represented the work force.

00:09:29.170 --> 00:09:30.790
The head of the community college.

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:32.490
The head of the Chamber of Commerce.

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:34.520
Everybody, all the poobahs were there,

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:36.090
and I brought my whole cabinet,

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:37.430
and we all basically said,

00:09:37.430 --> 00:09:40.040
Electrolux was there too and we said,

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:43.336
okay, we're gonna empty
our pockets full of chips

00:09:43.336 --> 00:09:45.080
and we're gonna make a pile

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:46.640
and we'll slide our pile

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:47.790
and this is a metaphor.

00:09:48.863 --> 00:09:50.622
Incentives in the pile of chips.

00:09:50.622 --> 00:09:52.830
We'll slide our pile of
chips across the table

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:54.800
to the management of Electrolux,

00:09:54.800 --> 00:09:57.080
and we will be able to save the factory

00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:58.340
and save the jobs,

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:00.410
and inside of that pile of incentives,

00:10:00.410 --> 00:10:02.527
it was really a list of incentives,

00:10:02.527 --> 00:10:04.095
but it's on the list,

00:10:04.095 --> 00:10:07.480
were things like zero taxes for 20 years,

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:10.500
and that was state and local taxes,

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:13.010
and we said we would help
to finance a new factory.

00:10:13.010 --> 00:10:15.180
As you can see this is
actually the factory

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:18.646
and it was old and it needed upgrades.

00:10:18.646 --> 00:10:23.646
The UAW said we're gonna
offer a level of incentives

00:10:24.067 --> 00:10:26.395
and they didn't want anyone to know

00:10:26.395 --> 00:10:28.640
how much they were willing to give

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:30.700
because they didn't want other employers

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:32.980
to be asking for those incentives.

00:10:32.980 --> 00:10:35.829
We put these incentives on the table

00:10:35.829 --> 00:10:39.520
and Electrolux takes
the list of incentives

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:43.753
and they go outside the
room for 17 minutes,

00:10:43.753 --> 00:10:47.280
and they come back in and they say, wow,

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:52.280
this is the most generous
any community has ever been

00:10:52.670 --> 00:10:55.357
in trying to keep jobs,

00:10:55.357 --> 00:11:00.357
but, there's nothing you can do

00:11:01.568 --> 00:11:03.705
to compensate for the fact

00:11:03.705 --> 00:11:08.705
that we can pay $1.57 an
hour in Juarez, Mexico,

00:11:09.713 --> 00:11:12.045
so we're going.

00:11:12.045 --> 00:11:16.330
There's nothing you can do, they said.

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:20.310
When they said that it was
like a nuclear bomb went off

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:22.342
in that little community.

00:11:22.342 --> 00:11:26.393
This is somebody leaving
on the last day of work.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.063
This is the implosion of the factory.

00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:35.943
This is the beautiful new
factory in Juarez, Mexico,

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:39.640
and I'm gonna go back
to him for one second,

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.083
because on the last of the month,

00:11:43.437 --> 00:11:46.430
during the month that
the last refrigerator

00:11:46.430 --> 00:11:48.490
came off the assembly line,

00:11:48.490 --> 00:11:50.941
the employees had a gathering

00:11:50.941 --> 00:11:54.915
that they called the last supper.

00:11:54.915 --> 00:11:58.260
It was at this big pavilion in Greenville.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:00.580
It was called Klackle's Orchard Pavilion.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:02.840
It was an indoor pavilion,

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:07.090
and the whole community
went and I went too,

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:09.110
event hough I was not invited.

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:10.937
This was for me.

00:12:10.937 --> 00:12:12.003
Can I just pause for a moment?

00:12:13.169 --> 00:12:14.750
This story.

00:12:14.750 --> 00:12:19.750
This has been my defining
moment as a leader.

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:24.290
This story, because it
was a failure on my part,

00:12:24.290 --> 00:12:26.686
and it was so hard.

00:12:26.686 --> 00:12:28.550
Back to the story.

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:31.024
I go to this dinner,

00:12:31.024 --> 00:12:34.147
and I walk into the pavilion,

00:12:34.147 --> 00:12:36.800
and there's 1,000 people there,

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:38.310
and they're sitting around tables

00:12:39.904 --> 00:12:41.825
eating out of box lunches

00:12:41.825 --> 00:12:43.990
and it's a sad band playing

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:46.431
or a band playing sad music.

00:12:46.431 --> 00:12:48.310
It was probably a sad band too.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:52.102
It was like a community wake,

00:12:52.102 --> 00:12:54.997
and I go up to the first table,

00:12:54.997 --> 00:12:57.870
and I'm not sure sure what I was.

00:12:57.870 --> 00:13:00.060
I just couldn't get it out of my head

00:13:00.908 --> 00:13:03.270
that I failed this huge
factory was leaving.

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:05.390
What was this community going to do?

00:13:05.390 --> 00:13:06.897
What could I do as Governor?

00:13:06.897 --> 00:13:08.478
I go up to the first table

00:13:08.478 --> 00:13:10.560
and this guy stands up
and he's got tattoos

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:12.140
and he's got his tiger hat on backwards,

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:15.850
and he pulls his two teenage
daughters next to me.

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:19.190
He says Governor, I want
you to meet my daughters.

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:22.281
He said, look at them.

00:13:22.281 --> 00:13:27.113
I have worked at this factory
he said, for 30 years.

00:13:28.271 --> 00:13:30.563
I'm 48 years old.

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:33.983
I went from high school to factory.

00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:38.140
My father worked at this factory, he said.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:42.230
My grandfather worked at this factory.

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:47.033
All I know is how to make refrigerators.

00:13:48.308 --> 00:13:52.230
Then he pulls his daughters in

00:13:52.230 --> 00:13:54.735
and he puts his hands
on his chest like this.

00:13:54.735 --> 00:13:59.735
So Gov, tell me, who
is ever gonna hire me?

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:05.083
Who is ever gonna hire me?

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:09.780
That question was asked by everybody

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:13.330
in the Klackle's Orchard Pavilion that day

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:17.240
and honestly it's been asked by everyone

00:14:17.240 --> 00:14:20.330
of the millions of
people who have lost jobs

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:23.730
in the 70,000 factories
that have shut down

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:25.673
since the beginning of this century.

00:14:26.920 --> 00:14:31.920
This experience, for me, seared my soul

00:14:32.568 --> 00:14:35.314
I stayed till the last person left.

00:14:35.314 --> 00:14:38.380
It wasn't just Electrolux.

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:40.560
I knew this was the
canary in the coal mine

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.057
for factories all over Michigan,

00:14:43.057 --> 00:14:45.293
and it was just the beginning.

00:14:47.710 --> 00:14:49.453
I can understand.

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:54.220
The president ran against globalization.

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:56.592
I used to campaign on it too.

00:14:56.592 --> 00:15:01.592
NAFTA and KAFTA have given
us the Shafta, I would say,

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:04.980
and I was elected on
that because I get it.

00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:06.453
I totally get it!

00:15:07.303 --> 00:15:11.760
I completely get why people
feel like these vacant factories

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:13.460
that are sitting on main streets

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:16.450
all across the industrial Midwest

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:21.280
are permanent scars on
our soul and our identity.

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:22.670
Even if they've been imploded

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:24.680
and there's just a vacant lot,

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:26.490
everybody remembers,

00:15:26.490 --> 00:15:28.661
oh that used to be the factory.

00:15:28.661 --> 00:15:29.861
That's where we worked.

00:15:29.861 --> 00:15:31.377
I totally get it.

00:15:31.377 --> 00:15:32.980
I get why he focused on that,

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:35.700
but the question is, is it really now,

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:39.182
in the second decade of this century,

00:15:39.182 --> 00:15:42.800
is it still all globalization?

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:47.800
Or is the other bad guy
for jobs, is it automation?

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:55.397
Actually about 13% of the job losses

00:15:55.397 --> 00:15:59.590
for manufacturing have really
been about globalization,

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:02.123
and the rest are due to automation.

00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:05.890
These two forces in this century

00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:07.410
and obviously globalization

00:16:08.261 --> 00:16:09.630
has been going on long before
the turn of the century

00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:12.077
but this is just when I
of course experienced it

00:16:12.077 --> 00:16:13.920
and that's why I tell that story.

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:17.370
The long term job killer isn't China,

00:16:17.370 --> 00:16:19.010
as the president keeps saying,

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:21.150
it is really automation,

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:23.330
and then what do we do about that?

00:16:23.330 --> 00:16:25.950
This graph is really instructive.

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:26.783
The first graph.

00:16:26.783 --> 00:16:28.003
Sorry the print is so small,

00:16:28.855 --> 00:16:31.070
but the first graph shows
manufacturing employment

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:32.530
in millions going down,

00:16:32.530 --> 00:16:35.930
and manufacturing output going up.

00:16:35.930 --> 00:16:37.510
Increases in productivity.

00:16:37.510 --> 00:16:42.000
Going up despite losses
of jobs in manufacturing,

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.163
and there's all these shock
studies that are out now.

00:16:46.163 --> 00:16:50.490
Automation to displace 20% to 25%!

00:16:50.490 --> 00:16:53.770
Eradicate a third of America's workforce!

00:16:53.770 --> 00:16:57.790
Machines will do half
our labor in eight years!

00:16:57.790 --> 00:16:58.623
Ahhh!

00:16:58.623 --> 00:16:59.456
We're gonna lose.

00:17:00.377 --> 00:17:01.734
We're all gonna die!

00:17:01.734 --> 00:17:03.320
We're gonna be taken over by robots!

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:04.788
What is gonna happen?

00:17:04.788 --> 00:17:06.952
If I told that guy, in Greenville,

00:17:06.952 --> 00:17:11.748
that there is an army of millions

00:17:11.748 --> 00:17:16.748
of fourth graders who would
be willing to do this job.

00:17:17.160 --> 00:17:21.412
Not for $1.57 an hour,
but say 40 cents an hour.

00:17:21.412 --> 00:17:23.945
He'd freak out.

00:17:23.945 --> 00:17:26.983
In fact, there's your army.

00:17:28.005 --> 00:17:32.300
The army of workers that can do the jobs

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:35.230
for so much less money,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:38.910
and Electrolux is now
delivering refrigerators

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:40.920
using autonomous vehicles,

00:17:40.920 --> 00:17:43.603
so the drivers too, gone.

00:17:44.467 --> 00:17:46.710
What are we gonna do?

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:49.130
What are we going to do?

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:50.710
There was this poll.

00:17:50.710 --> 00:17:52.350
This is to the human side of this.

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:56.090
There was a poll that was
done after the 2016 election.

00:17:56.090 --> 00:17:59.000
It was to blue collar workers
in the industrial Midwest

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.610
and this was the question that was asked.

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:02.170
Would you rather work full-time

00:18:02.170 --> 00:18:04.080
in a good paying factory job,

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:06.200
or in a salaried office job?

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:07.700
What do you think people said?

00:18:09.540 --> 00:18:12.710
Factory, yeah, by huge margins.

00:18:12.710 --> 00:18:15.690
72% said I'd rather work in a factory job.

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:19.997
28% in a salaried office job.

00:18:19.997 --> 00:18:22.520
The economy is shedding.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:26.683
The exact kind of jobs
that these workers want.

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:31.940
There is real pain out there
in the industrial Midwest

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:35.770
but the question is where are the jobs

00:18:35.770 --> 00:18:36.670
and where are they going?

00:18:36.670 --> 00:18:38.590
We all know that tech is dominating.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:42.703
The economy artificial intelligence, data,

00:18:42.703 --> 00:18:46.630
the whole we see it live
it in Silicon Valley.

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:48.651
Blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:18:48.651 --> 00:18:50.201
Tech is dominating the economy.

00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:53.420
The sector is leaving the rest in the dust

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:56.060
if you look at the growth companies.

00:18:56.060 --> 00:18:57.860
Obviously they're all tech companies

00:18:57.860 --> 00:18:59.610
or most of them are tech companies,

00:19:00.727 --> 00:19:04.628
and in fact, the top 10
tech bosses, billionaires,

00:19:04.628 --> 00:19:09.628
own more wealth than 40% of Americans.

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:15.920
Not only are people concerned
that the jobs are going away

00:19:16.430 --> 00:19:19.860
by the companies that are
coming out of Silicon Valley,

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:22.700
but there's also this
incredible inequality

00:19:22.700 --> 00:19:25.730
that is being created as a result

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:29.350
of big tech, data, AI, et cetera.

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:32.302
The global average salary
of the tech worker.

00:19:32.302 --> 00:19:34.590
About $135,000.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:38.580
If you're in that sector,
you're doing great as a worker.

00:19:38.580 --> 00:19:40.880
That's the global average,

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:44.590
but if you're not you may be left behind.

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:46.190
This income inequality.

00:19:46.190 --> 00:19:48.290
The blue line going down.

00:19:48.290 --> 00:19:49.750
The red line going up.

00:19:49.750 --> 00:19:52.088
The top 1% is the red.

00:19:52.088 --> 00:19:53.570
The bottom 50% is the blue.

00:19:53.570 --> 00:19:54.780
This is not a new story.

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:56.730
You've heard it talked about,

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:59.140
but it's just to underscore the fact

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:01.440
that historic inequality is happening

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:03.870
at the same time as tech is dominating,

00:20:03.870 --> 00:20:08.045
and as AI is replacing an awful lot

00:20:08.045 --> 00:20:10.870
of these jobs that were historically here.

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:13.430
To me this stat says it all.

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:16.575
Despite having a great
economy, we're told,

00:20:16.575 --> 00:20:19.000
you've got 40% of Americans,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.496
who don't even have $400
in a case of an emergency.

00:20:22.496 --> 00:20:26.910
40% of Americans, almost half the country.

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:30.080
You walk out and almost
half the people you see

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:33.200
will not have $400 in their bank account

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:35.330
in case of an emergency.

00:20:35.330 --> 00:20:37.600
This stat however, is really troubling.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:39.100
That 42% of Americans,

00:20:39.100 --> 00:20:41.480
have not even saved
$10,000 for retirement.

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:43.530
There is a boom coming.

00:20:43.530 --> 00:20:45.750
We've got a big problem,

00:20:45.750 --> 00:20:48.900
that we have to deal with as a country.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:52.286
This is the solution that is often cited.

00:20:52.286 --> 00:20:54.290
In a number of think tanks, et cetera.

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:57.130
Is UBI, universal basic income.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:21:01.470
Should we guarantee a
basic income for Americans?

00:21:01.470 --> 00:21:02.950
Who pays for that?

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:05.440
Even though they may
not be working at a job

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:09.561
to merit that pay?

00:21:09.561 --> 00:21:13.713
Silicon Valley in
particular is enamored this.

00:21:13.713 --> 00:21:16.210
This is why I've got
one with the pitchforks

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:18.486
because there's some concern,

00:21:18.486 --> 00:21:20.520
some realization that the tech industry

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:22.740
has created this income inequality

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:24.950
and they want to keep
the pitchforks at bay,

00:21:24.950 --> 00:21:28.818
and UBI might be a way
to assuage the masses.

00:21:28.818 --> 00:21:31.420
What is the answer?

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:34.940
We've been working here in this space

00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:38.070
through our work groups
on artificial intelligence

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:39.800
and we decided that,

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:41.920
let's see if there's a way we can get

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:45.630
AI to work with us, for
us, instead of against us,

00:21:45.630 --> 00:21:47.770
but let's not call it
artificial intelligence.

00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:49.910
Is there a way to instead call it

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:51.640
inclusive intelligence?

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:55.310
How do you get that
technology to work with people

00:21:55.310 --> 00:21:57.636
instead of replacing them?

00:21:57.636 --> 00:21:59.410
That's the question.

00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:00.750
Can there be this?

00:22:00.750 --> 00:22:03.630
What tech hath wrought,
tech can help solve!

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:05.860
Potentially, potentially!

00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:07.740
You've heard of Singularity, many of you.

00:22:07.740 --> 00:22:10.030
Singularity is the notion that

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:12.570
we will be merged with machines.

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:14.070
With robots, at some point.

00:22:14.070 --> 00:22:17.485
The robots are gonna take
over eventually totally,

00:22:17.485 --> 00:22:21.870
and as Elon Musk points out right now,

00:22:21.870 --> 00:22:23.830
you already are part cyborg

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:25.410
because every one of you,

00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:28.083
is there anybody here who
does not have a cell phone?

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:29.803
Nobody.

00:22:30.744 --> 00:22:32.177
You rely.

00:22:32.177 --> 00:22:33.010
You don't have a cell phone?

00:22:33.881 --> 00:22:35.099
Wow.

00:22:35.099 --> 00:22:35.932
You are the cell phone.

00:22:36.817 --> 00:22:38.469
Look you even get applause for that,

00:22:38.469 --> 00:22:40.378
because you're the only
human in the group.

00:22:40.378 --> 00:22:41.420
100% human.

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:43.380
What do these phones do?

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:45.600
They make you smarter.

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:47.203
They tell you where to go.

00:22:47.203 --> 00:22:48.576
They have your schedule.

00:22:48.576 --> 00:22:50.207
You can look anything up.

00:22:50.207 --> 00:22:52.170
You are so smart, because
you have a smartphone,

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:56.660
that you already are
merging with the robot.

00:22:56.660 --> 00:22:59.690
The question is, is there
a way to frame this,

00:22:59.690 --> 00:23:02.500
that is a positive way, a hopeful way,

00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:05.000
rather than a scary way?

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:09.220
Ken Goldberg who is here at U.C. Berkeley.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:10.910
He does all of the stuff with the robots.

00:23:10.910 --> 00:23:12.420
He heads the Robot whatever.

00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:14.686
I don't even know what it's called,

00:23:14.686 --> 00:23:15.950
but he has come up with a solution

00:23:15.950 --> 00:23:17.590
or a theory of the case,

00:23:17.590 --> 00:23:20.050
which is called, which
he terms multiplicity,

00:23:20.050 --> 00:23:22.700
which means that instead of being replaced

00:23:22.700 --> 00:23:27.570
that robots and AI can in
fact, enhance worker's skills,

00:23:27.570 --> 00:23:30.211
and make them better.

00:23:30.211 --> 00:23:31.500
Make them more valuable.

00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:33.980
If the training is right.

00:23:33.980 --> 00:23:37.560
If you can figure out how
to make it successful.

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:39.610
The thought experiment goes like this.

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:41.680
I'm sure many of you have seen this,

00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:44.554
but since the ATM was introduced,

00:23:44.554 --> 00:23:48.270
and people thought all the teller jobs

00:23:48.270 --> 00:23:51.253
are going away as a result of ATMs.

00:23:51.253 --> 00:23:54.010
Answer the question.

00:23:54.010 --> 00:23:56.400
Do we have more or fewer bank tellers

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:59.803
since the late 90s, when
the ATM became ubiquitous?

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:03.253
Not saying.

00:24:04.134 --> 00:24:05.267
We got more!

00:24:05.267 --> 00:24:06.776
More tellers!

00:24:06.776 --> 00:24:08.880
Since 2000, the number
of full time bank tellers

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:09.783
increased 2% a year,

00:24:10.805 --> 00:24:14.660
but the entire labor force
only grew .6% per year.

00:24:14.660 --> 00:24:16.460
Grew faster than the labor force,

00:24:16.460 --> 00:24:19.170
or same thing with bar code scanners.

00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:21.660
We are not going to have any real people

00:24:21.660 --> 00:24:23.640
at the grocery store anymore.

00:24:23.640 --> 00:24:25.120
You are gonna be doing the work.

00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:28.365
Have we got more or fewer cashiers?

00:24:28.365 --> 00:24:30.270
More.

00:24:30.270 --> 00:24:31.670
I lead you into that, didn't I?

00:24:31.670 --> 00:24:33.260
Yes, we have more.

00:24:33.260 --> 00:24:36.570
Again, growing at an annual rate of 2.1%

00:24:36.570 --> 00:24:39.070
when the labor force grew at .6%.

00:24:39.070 --> 00:24:40.450
What's going on with this?

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:41.283
It goes back.

00:24:42.424 --> 00:24:43.320
Remember the old luddites,

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:46.500
who threw the stuff in the loom

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:49.820
to make sure they still
had jobs doing weaving?

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:53.260
They didn't throw weavers out of work.

00:24:53.260 --> 00:24:58.260
It's a classic case of, classic economics.

00:24:58.830 --> 00:25:01.920
When you have something
created more cheaply,

00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:03.020
people are gonna buy it,

00:25:03.020 --> 00:25:05.527
and there will be more demand for it,

00:25:05.527 --> 00:25:07.230
and so instead of you having a suit

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:09.417
that you would have paid your whole

00:25:09.417 --> 00:25:12.820
annual salary for because
it was all done by hands,

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:15.000
now you can have a suit a day,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.630
if you buy it at H&amp;M,

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:20.250
because of the huge volume that's put out

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:22.480
and they're practically
throw away clothes.

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:26.840
The bottom line is there's more work,

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:30.700
more workers because of technology.

00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:33.850
In fact, James Bessen who is

00:25:33.850 --> 00:25:36.310
a professor at Boston University.

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:41.080
He actually had a study that he did,

00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:46.080
of 317 professions,

00:25:46.210 --> 00:25:49.090
where technology had been introduced,

00:25:49.090 --> 00:25:52.416
and in this effort,

00:25:52.416 --> 00:25:56.980
he said in all of the professions,

00:25:56.980 --> 00:26:01.170
all of the occupations that
had technology introduced,

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:06.170
there was only one where the
actual job was eliminated.

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:08.363
Only one.

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:12.100
Do you have any idea which one it was?

00:26:12.100 --> 00:26:13.823
Who said that?

00:26:15.480 --> 00:26:16.660
You are on it.

00:26:16.660 --> 00:26:18.143
Are you James Bessen?

00:26:20.802 --> 00:26:25.560
Only one guy's job was lost.

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:27.150
It was the elevator operator,

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:29.960
and even in some places they still exist.

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:31.794
This is what his point is.

00:26:31.794 --> 00:26:33.639
That employment grows significantly faster

00:26:33.639 --> 00:26:35.640
in occupations that use technology more,

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:38.900
and this is true not just
inside of those occupations

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:40.977
but also externally.

00:26:40.977 --> 00:26:44.949
Enrico Moretti, who also is
a professor here at Berkeley,

00:26:44.949 --> 00:26:48.730
he wrote a great book called
The New Geography of Jobs.

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:52.059
He studied the impact of
technology on employment

00:26:52.059 --> 00:26:54.920
around the employment.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:57.220
He uses as an example, Apple.

00:26:57.220 --> 00:26:59.681
The classic case, Apple employees,

00:26:59.681 --> 00:27:01.595
12,000 people or something like that

00:27:01.595 --> 00:27:04.100
in Cupertino at Apple headquarters,

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:07.560
but 60,000 in the economy around Apple

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:09.992
that aren't in even tech.

00:27:09.992 --> 00:27:12.620
The presence of that technology

00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:14.727
creates a dynamism that he suggests

00:27:14.727 --> 00:27:17.675
technology has a great impact on.

00:27:17.675 --> 00:27:19.850
I just want to focus for one second

00:27:19.850 --> 00:27:24.158
on one example of a technology, a product,

00:27:24.158 --> 00:27:28.159
