I happen to love this one,

00:39:57.298 --> 00:39:58.448
because it's very cool.

00:39:59.326 --> 00:40:02.884
In this regard, think about it.

00:40:02.884 --> 00:40:06.530
Data has become, as they say,

00:40:06.530 --> 00:40:09.450
the new resource, the new oil.

00:40:09.450 --> 00:40:12.268
All these companies making
huge amounts of money.

00:40:12.268 --> 00:40:15.920
Off of your data.

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:17.040
You're on Facebook.

00:40:17.040 --> 00:40:20.270
You're giving them all
sorts of information.

00:40:20.270 --> 00:40:23.770
They are so happy that you
are providing that to them

00:40:23.770 --> 00:40:26.360
because they can then
sell it to advertisers

00:40:26.360 --> 00:40:28.820
and make a huge amount of money off of you

00:40:28.820 --> 00:40:31.060
and you are just giving it to them.

00:40:31.060 --> 00:40:33.250
Not granted you get a
personalized experience

00:40:33.250 --> 00:40:35.600
in exchange, and the question is,

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:37.810
over and above that
personalized experience,

00:40:37.810 --> 00:40:40.500
who gets more out of the aggregate data

00:40:40.500 --> 00:40:43.760
that we're all giving to
Facebook, Google, et cetera,

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:47.510
and this goes beyond
just those experiences,

00:40:47.510 --> 00:40:49.460
but if you think about data

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:51.030
that is being accumulated through

00:40:51.030 --> 00:40:53.610
all of our devices.

00:40:53.610 --> 00:40:56.100
It's a lot of data,

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:58.540
and it is occupying a greater

00:40:58.540 --> 00:41:01.790
and greater percentage of the economy,

00:41:01.790 --> 00:41:06.790
and if this is being addressed
in California and Europe

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:11.683
have decided that you
are gonna own your data

00:41:11.683 --> 00:41:14.710
and that you have the ability

00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:17.720
to say what somebody
should do with your data.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:20.880
This is the General Data
Protection Regulation.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:24.330
Of Europe, and California's just starting

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:26.396
to experiment with this.

00:41:26.396 --> 00:41:28.020
They're not paying people for their data,

00:41:28.020 --> 00:41:29.570
but they are starting to say

00:41:29.570 --> 00:41:32.662
you have a property interest in your data

00:41:32.662 --> 00:41:36.685
and Mark Zuckerberg testifying,

00:41:36.685 --> 00:41:39.410
actually said every piece of content

00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:41.790
you share on Facebook, you own.

00:41:41.790 --> 00:41:45.423
You own it, and you're giving it away!

00:41:45.423 --> 00:41:50.329
Actually me and Chris Eldrin
who is a student here,

00:41:50.329 --> 00:41:55.120
we did a piece on this for CNN
that Facebook owes you money.

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:56.640
There's a whole group.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:58.110
There's a movement here.

00:41:58.110 --> 00:41:59.800
Facebook users unite.

00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:02.610
Data labor union launches
in the Netherlands.

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:04.590
Should we treat data as labor?

00:42:04.590 --> 00:42:06.450
Moving beyond free.

00:42:06.450 --> 00:42:10.010
What if people were paid for their data?

00:42:10.010 --> 00:42:13.160
The notion is instead of
a universal basic income

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:18.160
where you are given money for just being,

00:42:18.730 --> 00:42:22.350
maybe you could be given, being paid,

00:42:22.350 --> 00:42:24.720
for the amount of content you put up there

00:42:24.720 --> 00:42:28.100
and I used the analogy of
the Alaska permanent fund

00:42:29.252 --> 00:42:30.323
where in that case in that state,

00:42:31.284 --> 00:42:32.117
everybody gets a check.

00:42:33.035 --> 00:42:34.923
Last year it was $1,600 because

00:42:34.923 --> 00:42:36.530
of the natural resources that is beneath

00:42:36.530 --> 00:42:38.570
the land and the water.

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:41.200
The oil and gas natural resources.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:45.742
What if we considered
data to be a resource

00:42:45.742 --> 00:42:50.579
that requires some kind
of shared, profit sharing

00:42:50.579 --> 00:42:53.780
from the companies that are using it

00:42:53.780 --> 00:42:55.946
to make enormous profits?

00:42:55.946 --> 00:42:59.120
If AI, this is a Professor out of Yale

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.520
who is doing a lot of work on this.

00:43:01.520 --> 00:43:04.220
If AI represents 10% of the U.S. economy,

00:43:04.220 --> 00:43:06.730
he estimates that paying people for data

00:43:08.782 --> 00:43:10.293
would raise household
median income by $20,000

00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:13.442
which is a bigger increase
than the postwar era.

00:43:13.442 --> 00:43:16.517
That's assuming that you get to 10% of AI,

00:43:16.517 --> 00:43:18.212
in the economy,

00:43:18.212 --> 00:43:22.090
which actually I think is a
pretty conservative assumption.

00:43:22.090 --> 00:43:23.847
How would this work?

00:43:23.847 --> 00:43:26.040
A lot of questions about
what that would look like?

00:43:26.040 --> 00:43:28.050
How do you value the data?

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:31.509
Who negotiates the data for you?

00:43:31.509 --> 00:43:35.210
People are talking about
these data negotiation

00:43:35.210 --> 00:43:37.100
intermediaries that would actually

00:43:37.100 --> 00:43:39.970
do the negotiations on behalf of people

00:43:39.970 --> 00:43:41.580
to the companies.

00:43:41.580 --> 00:43:43.300
How to enforce your standards.

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:45.520
What is the role of government?

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:47.775
You look at the analogy of, for example,

00:43:47.775 --> 00:43:50.933
Spotify pays a micropayment, a royalty,

00:43:50.933 --> 00:43:55.420
to those who have their
intellectual property

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:58.230
listened to in music.

00:43:58.230 --> 00:43:59.850
Small micro payments.

00:43:59.850 --> 00:44:01.173
You create an account,

00:44:02.151 --> 00:44:03.984
where little bits of
micropayments might go

00:44:03.984 --> 00:44:05.574
and you wouldn't take the whole thing.

00:44:05.574 --> 00:44:06.553
The company still has to be profitable,

00:44:07.568 --> 00:44:09.070
but the amount of data of yours,

00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:11.750
that's being used to
create enormous profit,

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:14.270
the question is do you
deserve a little share

00:44:14.270 --> 00:44:16.870
of the profit from those companies?

00:44:16.870 --> 00:44:19.960
The next one is, I happen
to love competition,

00:44:19.960 --> 00:44:22.920
and I think that from a
public policy perspective,

00:44:22.920 --> 00:44:25.320
creating competition is a really cool way

00:44:25.320 --> 00:44:29.094
of getting policy adopted.

00:44:29.094 --> 00:44:34.094
Creating a competition for a
data driven workforce training

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:38.080
is I think a neat way to go.

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:39.900
There's you see the SunShot

00:44:39.900 --> 00:44:41.060
from the Department of Energy

00:44:41.060 --> 00:44:45.093
which was a competition
about getting solar cheap.

00:44:46.580 --> 00:44:48.600
The Race To the Top.

00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:51.090
The X prize were all competitions.

00:44:51.090 --> 00:44:54.660
In fact, the Workforce
Innovation Opportunity Act,

00:44:54.660 --> 00:44:58.707
right now we spend $10
billion to do training.

00:44:58.707 --> 00:44:59.610
$10 billion.

00:44:59.610 --> 00:45:01.380
If you took that $10 billion

00:45:01.380 --> 00:45:02.953
and created a competition,

00:45:03.794 --> 00:45:04.970
oh my God, it would blow the roof off.

00:45:04.970 --> 00:45:06.880
I use the Race To The Top For Education

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:08.830
as an example because what happened when

00:45:08.830 --> 00:45:11.319
the Obama Administration came in

00:45:11.319 --> 00:45:12.900
and they wanted to raise
high school standards,

00:45:12.900 --> 00:45:15.650
what they did was to say hey states,

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:18.700
here's $3.4 billion.

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:22.660
That $3.4 billion we'll
allow you to compete for it

00:45:22.660 --> 00:45:25.520
but the price to enter
is that you have to raise

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:27.300
your high school standards to essentially

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:29.567
be a college prep curriculum.

00:45:29.567 --> 00:45:31.510
$3.4 billion.

00:45:31.510 --> 00:45:35.098
48 states raised their standards!

00:45:35.098 --> 00:45:38.380
Just on the basis of that little carrot

00:45:38.380 --> 00:45:39.974
that was out there.

00:45:39.974 --> 00:45:41.330
$3.4 billion is not a little carrot,

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:44.190
but to states, all 50 states,

00:45:44.190 --> 00:45:47.150
that's a big incentive.

00:45:47.150 --> 00:45:49.680
If we have $10 billion being spent

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:52.590
for ineffective workforce
development training programs

00:45:52.590 --> 00:45:54.902
right now, and you put that out there

00:45:54.902 --> 00:45:56.789
as a competition among states,

00:45:56.789 --> 00:45:59.310
I am telling you, you
would get massive response,

00:45:59.310 --> 00:46:01.760
by both the private sector and governments

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:03.320
who want to work in ways

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:07.530
that would achieve great
workforce training outcomes.

00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:08.363
48 states.

00:46:08.363 --> 00:46:10.280
Who were the two states
that did not compete?

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:11.113
Do you know?

00:46:12.334 --> 00:46:13.733
Texas.

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:16.360
South Carolina.

00:46:16.360 --> 00:46:17.310
Those were the two,

00:46:18.166 --> 00:46:19.210
and you know what the
frustrating part was,

00:46:19.210 --> 00:46:21.860
we all competed, and in the first round,

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:23.760
only a couple of states got the money.

00:46:24.697 --> 00:46:26.305
We did not in Michigan.

00:46:26.305 --> 00:46:27.822
I was so bummed,

00:46:27.822 --> 00:46:28.740
because I cannot tell you how hard it was

00:46:29.597 --> 00:46:31.446
to get the legislature to act to do this,

00:46:31.446 --> 00:46:33.530
but nonetheless, you could
formulate this in a way

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:34.860
where everybody gets a little piece

00:46:34.860 --> 00:46:36.533
if you have a $10 billion fund.

00:46:37.910 --> 00:46:42.910
Last one, is the idea of these
new workforce arrangements

00:46:46.261 --> 00:46:51.261
where people are creating
employment through Uber,

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:54.850
through an app, through
Task Rabbit, et cetera.

00:46:54.850 --> 00:46:57.420
How do you create portable
benefits for them?

00:46:57.420 --> 00:46:58.800
How do you create an environment

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:01.040
where they are covered in some way,

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:04.982
because right now they
have got no benefits.

00:47:04.982 --> 00:47:09.190
The notion of course that
a college graduate today

00:47:09.190 --> 00:47:10.950
should expect to have 30 different jobs,

00:47:10.950 --> 00:47:12.060
three separate careers,

00:47:12.060 --> 00:47:15.070
over their 60 year working lives,

00:47:15.070 --> 00:47:17.282
and this arrow up here.

00:47:17.282 --> 00:47:18.949
1995, 2005, to 2015.

00:47:20.338 --> 00:47:24.690
57% increase in the rise
in alternative work,

00:47:24.690 --> 00:47:27.070
where you are on your own

00:47:27.070 --> 00:47:29.660
probably using an app
to be able to connect

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:30.920
with potential customers.

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:33.470
94% of the net employment growth

00:47:33.470 --> 00:47:37.210
in the U.S. economies from 2005 to 2015,

00:47:37.210 --> 00:47:41.200
94% have occurred in these alternative

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:43.920
work arrangement spaces.

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:45.490
That's a huge increase

00:47:45.490 --> 00:47:47.330
and we haven't done anything about it,

00:47:47.330 --> 00:47:49.720
and here's the kicker is that 80%

00:47:49.720 --> 00:47:51.860
of independent contractors and freelancers

00:47:51.860 --> 00:47:54.372
preferred alternative work arrangements

00:47:54.372 --> 00:47:56.390
to standard employment.

00:47:56.390 --> 00:47:58.640
They prefer that kind of flexibility,

00:47:58.640 --> 00:47:59.620
that kind of lifestyle.

00:47:59.620 --> 00:48:01.160
They can choose when to work,

00:48:01.160 --> 00:48:02.990
but they are completely on their own

00:48:02.990 --> 00:48:04.440
when it comes to retirement,

00:48:04.440 --> 00:48:06.152
when it comes to healthcare, et cetera.

00:48:06.152 --> 00:48:08.138
What do we do about that?

00:48:08.138 --> 00:48:11.390
In the old world, everybody
works for something

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:13.140
like working for the
University of California.

00:48:13.140 --> 00:48:15.660
You got your employment relationship.

00:48:15.660 --> 00:48:17.643
You also had contractors
who had individual

00:48:17.643 --> 00:48:21.140
relationships with people
who were hiring them.

00:48:21.140 --> 00:48:23.550
These independent workers in the middle

00:48:23.550 --> 00:48:25.970
are going through an app.

00:48:25.970 --> 00:48:29.213
They really are totally a
different work arrangement.

00:48:29.213 --> 00:48:31.160
They're unable to organize.

00:48:31.160 --> 00:48:33.070
They're unable to collectively bargain

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:34.260
for wages or benefits.

00:48:34.260 --> 00:48:36.610
They're not protected by civil rights

00:48:36.610 --> 00:48:38.410
of anti discrimination legislation.

00:48:38.410 --> 00:48:39.830
They're unable to receive benefits

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:43.400
without being classified as employees,

00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:48.280
and this is the battle
between traditional employers.

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:50.320
They don't want to take
them on as employees.

00:48:50.320 --> 00:48:52.060
They don't want to have to be responsible

00:48:52.060 --> 00:48:53.483
for all of those benefits.

00:48:54.600 --> 00:48:56.231
How do you do this?

00:48:56.231 --> 00:48:58.820
We've gotta create a system

00:48:58.820 --> 00:49:01.619
where you have a safe harbor for employers

00:49:01.619 --> 00:49:05.580
to offer portable benefits, without I-Ws.

00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:07.988
Those are independent workers.

00:49:07.988 --> 00:49:10.300
Without being classified as employers.

00:49:10.300 --> 00:49:14.010
They should be able to offer some kind

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:16.070
of series of accounts,

00:49:16.070 --> 00:49:19.130
where they could do the tax
withholding, social security,

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:20.650
and Medicare contributions,

00:49:20.650 --> 00:49:22.940
unemployment insurance,
retirement savings,

00:49:22.940 --> 00:49:24.662
create learning accounts,

00:49:24.662 --> 00:49:29.662
while allowing that person to
be a free agent essentially.

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:34.460
What's the world that that looks like?

00:49:34.460 --> 00:49:37.063
There is this portable benefits issue

00:49:37.063 --> 00:49:39.346
is being discussed all over the place.

00:49:39.346 --> 00:49:41.190
It's being discussed in Europe.

00:49:41.190 --> 00:49:43.110
It's being discussed
through legislation here.

00:49:43.110 --> 00:49:45.700
Portable Benefits for
Independent Workers Act.

00:49:45.700 --> 00:49:47.700
There are state experiments in California,

00:49:47.700 --> 00:49:50.310
Washington, New Jersey, New York.

00:49:50.310 --> 00:49:52.680
Just a quick example of
this from another country,

00:49:52.680 --> 00:49:55.210
is that the government of Singapore,

00:49:55.210 --> 00:49:58.670
has given as a benefit to people

00:49:58.670 --> 00:50:01.656
these individual learning accounts,

00:50:01.656 --> 00:50:03.570
which go with them wherever they are.

00:50:03.570 --> 00:50:05.691
They started out, the
government actually paid

00:50:05.691 --> 00:50:09.520
$500 for every worker over
25 years old in Singapore

00:50:09.520 --> 00:50:14.370
to be able to get educated as
a life long learning account

00:50:14.370 --> 00:50:17.770
and you can take a class
in flower arranging

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:19.110
or cybersecurity.

00:50:19.110 --> 00:50:20.163
Whatever is it.

00:50:21.203 --> 00:50:22.620
They just started doing
this two years ago,

00:50:22.620 --> 00:50:25.650
so there hasn't been an
evaluation of the program yet,

00:50:25.650 --> 00:50:28.120
but the bottom line is portable benefits

00:50:28.120 --> 00:50:30.300
have got to be a solution

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:33.510
for the workforce of the 21st century.

00:50:33.510 --> 00:50:34.343
Those five ideas.

00:50:34.343 --> 00:50:36.220
Subsidized trial employment.

00:50:36.220 --> 00:50:37.740
Data driven training.

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:39.400
Paying people for their data.

00:50:39.400 --> 00:50:40.500
Competition.

00:50:40.500 --> 00:50:42.910
Flexible portable benefits,

00:50:42.910 --> 00:50:44.603
and here's the finish!

00:50:45.643 --> 00:50:49.190
Who is gonna get displaced
workers into good jobs?

00:50:49.190 --> 00:50:52.610
Who will sustain the middle
class in the digital era?

00:50:52.610 --> 00:50:54.330
Who will save us on the planet

00:50:54.330 --> 00:50:56.813
from death and destruction?

00:50:56.813 --> 00:50:58.880
Who can ensure AI will
be a force for good?

00:50:58.880 --> 00:51:01.420
Is it President Trump?

00:51:01.420 --> 00:51:04.048
Or our next president, whoever she is?

00:51:04.048 --> 00:51:08.680
Is it Elon Musk or Bill
Gates or Mark Zuckerberg?

00:51:08.680 --> 00:51:10.610
Is is Gavin Newsom?

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:15.610
Or is it Oski the Bear
and Berkeley brain power?

