$10,000.

00:53:03.420 --> 00:53:05.760
You have to be trained in an area of need,

00:53:05.760 --> 00:53:08.250
and we had identified what
those were in Michigan.

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:12.063
Like nursing and tech, et cetera,

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:14.780
and we would pay for your tuition,

00:53:14.780 --> 00:53:17.326
and we had within months,

00:53:17.326 --> 00:53:20.050
the whole program was subscribed to.

00:53:20.050 --> 00:53:22.296
I went back to the federal government

00:53:22.296 --> 00:53:23.810
and said instead of this TAA,

00:53:23.810 --> 00:53:26.440
and workforce can you
just give me flexibility

00:53:26.440 --> 00:53:28.710
and we could add more people to this.

00:53:28.710 --> 00:53:31.140
We added another 50,000 people

00:53:31.140 --> 00:53:33.170
to be able to get trained in an area

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:34.700
that they wanted to get trained in,

00:53:34.700 --> 00:53:35.930
but here's the kicker on it,

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:38.710
is that a lot of people
who are like 48 years old,

00:53:38.710 --> 00:53:40.310
like the guy I was talking about,

00:53:40.310 --> 00:53:42.870
they don't necessarily want
to go to a community college

00:53:42.870 --> 00:53:44.498
and sit next to a 21
year old and do calculus,

00:53:44.498 --> 00:53:49.420
when they can't even
remember whether they.

00:53:49.420 --> 00:53:51.243
They don't remember
percentages from high school.

00:53:51.243 --> 00:53:53.670
This wasn't something they took.

00:53:53.670 --> 00:53:55.690
This is why doing training,

00:53:55.690 --> 00:53:58.350
in a way that respects where people are,

00:53:58.350 --> 00:54:00.940
and takes them to the
next level at their pace

00:54:00.940 --> 00:54:03.890
and in their way, is a
really important strategy,

00:54:03.890 --> 00:54:07.378
and in a lot of ways
we had the union halls

00:54:07.378 --> 00:54:08.680
be open to be doing the training,

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:10.280
and bringing training into them

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:12.770
because they were more
comfortable in that setting,

00:54:12.770 --> 00:54:14.873
but training has to be flexible like that.

00:54:20.384 --> 00:54:22.160
- [Man] If you wanna come up,

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:24.240
and just wait to ask the question.

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:26.284
- [Woman] Thank you very much.

00:54:26.284 --> 00:54:28.051
These are some really excellent ideas.

00:54:28.051 --> 00:54:29.920
Most of which I had
never thought of before.

00:54:29.920 --> 00:54:31.570
I need to process a little bit,

00:54:31.570 --> 00:54:34.010
but one of the things I wanted to ask you,

00:54:34.010 --> 00:54:36.710
was could some of these ideas,

00:54:36.710 --> 00:54:39.240
not be compatible with something

00:54:39.240 --> 00:54:41.140
like a universal basic income,

00:54:41.140 --> 00:54:44.420
because for example your Alaska analogy

00:54:44.420 --> 00:54:47.140
essentially was like a
universal basic income.

00:54:47.140 --> 00:54:49.038
That is what the does.

00:54:49.038 --> 00:54:50.330
It doesn't actually depend on their skills

00:54:50.330 --> 00:54:53.888
or their age or their
training or the employer.

00:54:53.888 --> 00:54:56.870
I just wanted to ask,
are these substitutes,

00:54:56.870 --> 00:54:59.683
or could they be
compatible with something?

00:55:00.791 --> 00:55:02.410
- The paying people for data

00:55:02.410 --> 00:55:05.880
is sort of like a universal
basic income concept.

00:55:05.880 --> 00:55:07.540
Similar to it.

00:55:07.540 --> 00:55:11.460
In the Alaska situation,
people get compensated,

00:55:11.460 --> 00:55:13.660
because they own the state,

00:55:13.660 --> 00:55:15.870
and the question is what's the analogy

00:55:15.870 --> 00:55:18.070
for a country where you have a state,

00:55:18.070 --> 00:55:20.052
like in Michigan, we don't have

00:55:20.052 --> 00:55:21.969
huge oil and gas resources,

00:55:21.969 --> 00:55:23.940
where maybe we would have to think

00:55:23.940 --> 00:55:26.265
of a different way of doing it,

00:55:26.265 --> 00:55:27.691
and the question is,

00:55:27.691 --> 00:55:29.690
is there a way to do it,

00:55:29.690 --> 00:55:34.690
that doesn't cause people's
hair to catch on fire

00:55:34.840 --> 00:55:38.010
because you are redistributing
mass amounts of income

00:55:38.010 --> 00:55:39.590
through tax increases,

00:55:39.590 --> 00:55:41.730
and so the question is,

00:55:41.730 --> 00:55:43.200
is there a different way of looking at

00:55:43.200 --> 00:55:45.526
a universal basic income,

00:55:45.526 --> 00:55:46.990
which guarantees people some dignity.

00:55:46.990 --> 00:55:48.540
The other thing I would say though,

00:55:48.540 --> 00:55:50.610
there's a lot of pushback from people

00:55:50.610 --> 00:55:53.864
who feel like I don't want
to just be given a check.

00:55:53.864 --> 00:55:58.864
I want to have there be
an exchange for my input.

00:56:00.140 --> 00:56:03.590
Whether it's data, or my work, my sweat.

00:56:03.590 --> 00:56:05.170
Whatever it is.

00:56:05.170 --> 00:56:07.160
That's the pushback you get.

00:56:07.160 --> 00:56:10.310
I think from people on the left even

00:56:10.310 --> 00:56:13.070
who are saying, UBI, the concept is okay,

00:56:13.070 --> 00:56:15.330
but you want to respect the dignity

00:56:15.330 --> 00:56:16.830
of people who want to be able

00:56:16.830 --> 00:56:18.993
to be engaged in employment.

00:56:20.591 --> 00:56:22.250
- [Woman] Thank you for your talk.

00:56:22.250 --> 00:56:24.730
Would you mind talking about the fact

00:56:24.730 --> 00:56:28.640
that I believe there are millions of jobs

00:56:28.640 --> 00:56:31.001
in the manufacturing
sector in this country

00:56:31.001 --> 00:56:34.190
that go unfilled over
long periods of time.

00:56:34.190 --> 00:56:36.850
I think especially since
the end of the recession

00:56:36.850 --> 00:56:38.915
and I'd like to, I don't believe

00:56:38.915 --> 00:56:40.840
that you've talked about that

00:56:40.840 --> 00:56:42.220
and where's the problem,

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:44.360
and how do you solve that problem?

00:56:44.360 --> 00:56:47.660
- Yeah, I would say
that there is definitely

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:52.660
a mismatch of demand and
supply in certain areas.

00:56:53.421 --> 00:56:56.949
Especially with a low unemployment rate.

00:56:56.949 --> 00:57:00.330
There's a lot of jobs
that are going unfilled.

00:57:00.330 --> 00:57:03.051
A lot of the work in
manufacturing now though

00:57:03.051 --> 00:57:05.685
requires a level of skill

00:57:05.685 --> 00:57:08.680
that you wouldn't have needed in the past,

00:57:08.680 --> 00:57:12.290
so it requires somebody to
have some kind of certification

00:57:12.290 --> 00:57:16.020
to do the CNC, the machines,

00:57:16.020 --> 00:57:17.570
that actually do the manufacturing.

00:57:17.570 --> 00:57:18.663
It's sophisticated.

00:57:19.507 --> 00:57:21.076
In fact, in one of the last years

00:57:21.076 --> 00:57:21.950
when I was Governor.

00:57:21.950 --> 00:57:23.570
We cut the ribbon on a factory

00:57:24.475 --> 00:57:26.387
that was an engine plant,

00:57:26.387 --> 00:57:28.031
where they weren't hiring anybody,

00:57:28.031 --> 00:57:29.608
who didn't have a college degree,

00:57:29.608 --> 00:57:30.441
because you had to have people

00:57:31.489 --> 00:57:32.343
who knew how to operate the robots,

00:57:33.242 --> 00:57:34.989
and how to maintain a robotic line,

00:57:34.989 --> 00:57:36.881
and that's where manufacturing has gone.

00:57:36.881 --> 00:57:38.901
That's why we're seeing
some of the reshoring

00:57:38.901 --> 00:57:40.670
is because it's cheaper to have robots

00:57:40.670 --> 00:57:41.663
and fewer people,

00:57:42.781 --> 00:57:44.409
but the people who you hire,

00:57:44.409 --> 00:57:45.450
they've got to know how to operate.

00:57:45.450 --> 00:57:47.490
It gets back to the question of training.

00:57:47.490 --> 00:57:50.620
If there's a gap, it's a training gap.

00:57:50.620 --> 00:57:51.480
Here's the problem,

00:57:51.480 --> 00:57:55.729
is that when you've got a
very technology driven job,

00:57:55.729 --> 00:57:58.360
whether it's a coding job,

00:57:58.360 --> 00:58:00.760
or working with robots job,

00:58:00.760 --> 00:58:03.750
the employer expects the employees to come

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:05.450
fully trained up.

00:58:05.450 --> 00:58:07.620
They're not often willing to take the risk

00:58:07.620 --> 00:58:09.353
on training someone themselves,

00:58:10.262 --> 00:58:11.240
which gets back to this question

00:58:12.161 --> 00:58:14.240
about can the government
offer a subsidized

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:17.700
training period, so somebody
can learn those skills,

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:20.765
where the employer doesn't
have to pay fully for it

00:58:20.765 --> 00:58:23.465
and then transition over
to the employee training.

00:58:23.465 --> 00:58:25.756
Right now they don't.

00:58:25.756 --> 00:58:27.310
They aren't taking that risk

00:58:27.310 --> 00:58:29.920
on hiring somebody who doesn't have

00:58:29.920 --> 00:58:32.280
a computer engineering
degree from Berkeley

00:58:32.280 --> 00:58:36.200
and that's cutting out a
whole swath of the country

00:58:36.200 --> 00:58:38.900
and only a third of the
country have college degrees.

00:58:38.900 --> 00:58:40.250
What are we doing for them?

00:58:41.838 --> 00:58:44.596
- [Man] Good evening.

00:58:44.596 --> 00:58:46.130
I have a question regarding taxation.

00:58:46.130 --> 00:58:48.140
As we move toward a knowledge economy,

00:58:48.140 --> 00:58:49.740
and a data driven economy,

00:58:49.740 --> 00:58:53.080
what are the appropriate ways to capture

00:58:53.080 --> 00:58:55.159
that revenue stream,

00:58:55.159 --> 00:58:56.700
and where do you see
that going in the future?

00:58:56.700 --> 00:58:59.377
- Well, this is a really
interesting question.

00:58:59.377 --> 00:59:02.100
My husband Dan who is sitting there

00:59:02.100 --> 00:59:04.250
was just talking to me
about that this morning.

00:59:04.250 --> 00:59:06.350
You want to share your idea?

00:59:06.350 --> 00:59:07.313
No, okay.

00:59:08.207 --> 00:59:10.240
(audience laughing)

00:59:10.240 --> 00:59:12.491
But it's a really important question,

00:59:12.491 --> 00:59:14.570
because we have a tax structure,

00:59:14.570 --> 00:59:17.800
that especially with the latest tax plan

00:59:17.800 --> 00:59:20.670
that really drives all the revenue up.

00:59:20.670 --> 00:59:22.610
Benefits the people at the top

00:59:22.610 --> 00:59:24.829
and the people at the bottom

00:59:24.829 --> 00:59:26.010
are left without anything.

00:59:26.010 --> 00:59:28.490
Think about a structure
that's much different

00:59:28.490 --> 00:59:31.770
that really does allow
people to make the money

00:59:31.770 --> 00:59:34.000
that they need to make and earn the income

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:34.900
they need to earn,

00:59:36.167 --> 00:59:39.920
but gives a slice of that
to the folks at the bottom

00:59:39.920 --> 00:59:42.240
because this disparity
that has been created

00:59:42.240 --> 00:59:44.680
by the structural changes in our economy,

00:59:44.680 --> 00:59:47.020
is not benefiting everybody,

00:59:47.020 --> 00:59:51.950
and it's a redistribution
question that you asked,

00:59:51.950 --> 00:59:55.620
and whenever you talk about
redistribution in Washington DC

00:59:55.620 --> 00:59:57.990
people's hair really do catch on fire.

00:59:57.990 --> 01:00:01.160
The issue is can we elect people

01:00:01.160 --> 01:00:02.910
who are not afraid to say, hey,

01:00:02.910 --> 01:00:04.810
who are we as a society?

01:00:04.810 --> 01:00:06.370
Are we gonna create a safety net?

01:00:06.370 --> 01:00:07.620
Who are we?

01:00:07.620 --> 01:00:10.700
Are we going to allow people
to be sleeping under bridges?

01:00:10.700 --> 01:00:13.078
Because we haven't cared for them.

01:00:13.078 --> 01:00:15.680
What kind of community
do we want to create,

01:00:15.680 --> 01:00:19.240
and one would expect
that in the 21st century,

01:00:19.240 --> 01:00:23.462
people would say hey,
we share this planet.

01:00:23.462 --> 01:00:27.040
We share the air, as
terrible as it is today,

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:30.620
but we share the salaries
for the firefighters

01:00:30.620 --> 01:00:34.850
who are out there fighting this mess.

01:00:34.850 --> 01:00:37.840
We share responsibility for the roads

01:00:37.840 --> 01:00:39.930
that you drove on to get here.

01:00:39.930 --> 01:00:43.853
We share responsibility for
this fabulous University.

01:00:44.805 --> 01:00:47.209
We should be sharing a
responsibility for one another

01:00:47.209 --> 01:00:48.590
and keep that safety net intact,

01:00:48.590 --> 01:00:51.040
and people once you start to talk about

01:00:51.040 --> 01:00:53.377
taking something from someone,

01:00:53.377 --> 01:00:56.220
that's when people freak
out until they need it.

01:00:56.220 --> 01:00:58.100
Until they need those services.

01:00:58.100 --> 01:01:01.610
You would hope that you hold
one end of the safety net.

01:01:01.610 --> 01:01:02.920
I hold the other.

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:05.970
We hold it to make sure
that nobody falls through.

01:01:05.970 --> 01:01:08.160
One day I may need it.

01:01:08.160 --> 01:01:10.064
One day you may need it,

01:01:10.064 --> 01:01:11.100
but in the end we hope that

01:01:11.100 --> 01:01:13.010
we could create a world

01:01:13.010 --> 01:01:15.060
where nobody gets left behind.

01:01:15.060 --> 01:01:17.150
Where we are like the Marines.

01:01:17.150 --> 01:01:18.920
Nobody gets left behind.

01:01:18.920 --> 01:01:19.980
We're all going.

01:01:19.980 --> 01:01:22.060
We're not leaving anybody back.

01:01:22.060 --> 01:01:24.010
Why can't we create a world like that?

01:01:24.010 --> 01:01:26.390
Why can't we talk about
sharing a little bit more?

01:01:26.390 --> 01:01:27.570
It's a great question.

01:01:27.570 --> 01:01:29.170
Maybe you should run for office.

01:01:33.460 --> 01:01:36.023
- [Man] You mentioned a couple times

01:01:36.023 --> 01:01:37.953
and I kept hearing the
word union and labor.

01:01:37.953 --> 01:01:41.800
Where does union fit
into the private public

01:01:41.800 --> 01:01:44.290
relationship with training going forward,

01:01:44.290 --> 01:01:47.150
because it's always been
where people have gone

01:01:47.150 --> 01:01:49.223
when they needed training.

01:01:49.223 --> 01:01:51.509
- Exactly, and it's a great moment

01:01:51.509 --> 01:01:54.010
for the unions to think about their role

01:01:54.010 --> 01:01:56.070
in this digital economy.

01:01:56.070 --> 01:02:01.070
One could imagine that
there would be a data union,

01:02:01.870 --> 01:02:03.500
or one of the existing unions

01:02:03.500 --> 01:02:05.363
would take on the negotiation,

01:02:06.705 --> 01:02:10.200
for your compensation,
for your inputs on data.

01:02:10.200 --> 01:02:12.290
You could imagine a world where

01:02:12.290 --> 01:02:15.208
the unions become the
brokers of great skill.

01:02:15.208 --> 01:02:19.930
Rather than people see
unions in these silos,

01:02:19.930 --> 01:02:23.560
but when I think about
the UAW for example,

01:02:23.560 --> 01:02:25.070
which is the union I'm most familiar with

01:02:25.070 --> 01:02:26.809
from Michigan, United Auto Workers,

01:02:26.809 --> 01:02:31.570
they were the place where
the auto workers went

01:02:31.570 --> 01:02:34.020
to get trained workers.

01:02:34.020 --> 01:02:35.542
They were the place.

01:02:35.542 --> 01:02:39.186
In a 21st century, why not think about

01:02:39.186 --> 01:02:42.150
those portable benefits for the workers

01:02:42.150 --> 01:02:44.800
who have alternative work arrangements.

01:02:44.800 --> 01:02:48.330
There should be a union or a negotiator

01:02:48.330 --> 01:02:53.330
or some entity that is pooling
people's desires together

01:02:53.840 --> 01:02:58.500
and has a common face to Uber or whomever.

01:02:58.500 --> 01:03:00.501
To be able to negotiate for them.

01:03:00.501 --> 01:03:03.830
I think the unions absolutely can have

01:03:03.830 --> 01:03:08.830
a new role if they look
as well, at themselves,

01:03:09.790 --> 01:03:12.420
as transitioning in the 21st century.

01:03:12.420 --> 01:03:15.756
Not just building on old models,

01:03:15.756 --> 01:03:17.820
but looking to the future.

01:03:17.820 --> 01:03:19.290
I think that they could.

01:03:19.290 --> 01:03:20.300
Some of them are doing it.

01:03:20.300 --> 01:03:21.350
Some of them are not.

01:03:22.940 --> 01:03:25.750
- [Woman] I find it interesting
that you mention Walmart.

01:03:25.750 --> 01:03:28.852
Something is very broken in our country,

01:03:28.852 --> 01:03:31.335
because workers at Walmart,

01:03:31.335 --> 01:03:33.980
a lot of them are on food stamps,

01:03:33.980 --> 01:03:37.133
because they're not making a living wage.

01:03:37.133 --> 01:03:42.133
The Walton family has this
enormous enormous fortune

01:03:42.150 --> 01:03:45.230
where they decide how to spend the money.

01:03:45.230 --> 01:03:47.398
It's not just looking to the government,

01:03:47.398 --> 01:03:51.407
it sounds like looking to the government

01:03:51.407 --> 01:03:56.407
to expect something
more humane from Walmart

01:03:58.640 --> 01:04:00.263
and companies like that.

01:04:01.190 --> 01:04:03.314
- It's interesting, isn't it?

01:04:03.314 --> 01:04:06.035
That there isn't more accountability,

01:04:06.035 --> 01:04:09.900
at the level of ownership of companies.

01:04:09.900 --> 01:04:13.610
Like we, you probably
have a retirement fund,

01:04:13.610 --> 01:04:15.470
and you have some shares of stock.

01:04:15.470 --> 01:04:17.505
I don't know if you have Walmart of not

01:04:17.505 --> 01:04:19.030
but the bottom line is, a lot of times,

01:04:19.030 --> 01:04:21.930
we don't exercise any
power as shareholders

01:04:21.930 --> 01:04:25.540
to insist that the
companies that we invest in

01:04:25.540 --> 01:04:28.050
behave in a way that would make them

01:04:28.050 --> 01:04:29.210
be part of the community,

01:04:29.210 --> 01:04:30.603
and leading as well.

01:04:31.890 --> 01:04:34.350
We identify as shareholder.

01:04:34.350 --> 01:04:36.910
Fudiciary responsibility of shareholders

01:04:36.910 --> 01:04:38.620
to maximize profits,

01:04:38.620 --> 01:04:40.671
and that's the only thing,

01:04:40.671 --> 01:04:43.590
that a CEO looks to, is maximizing profit.

01:04:43.590 --> 01:04:46.340
Maybe we should look at
GDP in a different way.

01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:50.160
Maybe it should be about
wellbeing of the citizens

01:04:50.160 --> 01:04:51.812
of the country.

01:04:51.812 --> 01:04:54.600
Rather than just wellbeing of
the pocketbooks of the CEOs.

01:04:54.600 --> 01:04:56.840
I wish I had a good answer
for how to fix this.

01:04:56.840 --> 01:04:58.160
If I were Bob Reich.

01:04:58.160 --> 01:04:59.913
I would tell you the answer,

01:05:00.889 --> 01:05:02.672
but I will leave that to him,

01:05:02.672 --> 01:05:04.350
because I know he spoke
at the Weinstock series.

01:05:04.350 --> 01:05:06.300
You can find him anywhere, as you know.

01:05:07.900 --> 01:05:10.450
It's a great question about how to hold

01:05:10.450 --> 01:05:12.860
these companies to account for their role

01:05:12.860 --> 01:05:16.092
in the creation of a more equal society.

